 = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1996\u20131998\n| nationalteam2 = [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 8\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2011\u20132015\n| managerclubs1 = [[Borussia Dortmund II]]\n| manageryears2 = 2015\u20132019\n| managerclubs2 = [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]\n| manageryears3 = 2019\u2013\n| managerclubs3 = [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]]\n}}\n'''David Wagner''' (born 19 October 1971) is a professional [[association football|football]] [[Manager (association football)|manager]] and former player who is the manager of [[Bundesliga]] club [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]].\n\nHe grew up in West Germany and made his professional debut with [[Eintracht Frankfurt]] in 1990 and played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]] for several clubs in the first and second divisions of [[German football league system|German football]]. The son of an American father and German mother, Wagner played for the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]], earning eight caps between 1996 and 1998.\n\nFrom 2011 to 2015, he managed [[Borussia Dortmund II]]. Wagner left in November 2015 to take the job at [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]], which he led to the [[Premier League]] via the [[2017 EFL Championship play-off Final]]. He left Huddersfield in January 2019, soon afterwards taking the manager position at Bundesliga club Schalke 04 in July 2019.\n\n==Early life==\nWagner was born in [[Frankfurt]], West Germany.<ref name=\"ruhr24\" /> His biological father is from [[Thailand]],<ref name=\"11 Freunde\">{{Cite web|url=https://11freunde.de/artikel/wie-david-wagner-schalke-wiederbelebt/page/1|title=Wagners gr\u00f6\u00dfte Leistung|first=Ron|last=Ulrich|work=11 Freunde|publisher=11 Freunde GmbH & Co. KG|date=29 September 2019|accessdate=20 December 2019|language=de}}</ref> his mother is German.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://americansoccernow.com/articles/american-david-wagner-now-coaching-in-england|title=ASN: American David Wagner Now Coaching in England|website=americansoccernow.com|access-date=14 January 2019}}</ref> Before his birth, Wagner's mother married an American.<ref name=\"11 Freunde\" />\n\n==Playing career==\nIn 1996, Wagner was recruited along with fellow [[Bundesliga]] player [[Michael Mason (soccer)|Michael Mason]] by manager [[Steve Sampson]] into the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]] despite never having seen them play. Sampson had been recommended Wagner and Mason and made aware of their American background by U.S. player [[Thomas Dooley]], who like them was also raised in Germany. Wagner had a United States passport, but had played for Germany's [[Germany national under-18 football team|U18]] and [[Germany national under-21 football team|U21]] teams earlier in his career. This gave him additional credibility with Sampson but posed a problem as he risked being considered ineligible to play for the United States.\n\nWagner made his debut in a friendly 3\u20131 win over [[El Salvador national football team|El Salvador]] in Los Angeles on 30 August 1996, in which he was substituted at half-time for [[Brian McBride]]. He made five appearances the following year and two more in 1998, all but one as a starter.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wagner, David |url=https://www.national-football-teams.com/player/28278/David_Wagner.html |publisher=National Football Teams |accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=1996 Lineups |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/mens-national-team/lineups/1996-lineups |publisher=US Soccer |accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1997, after [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]] lost to the United States in a [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|World Cup qualifying]] match in which Wagner played, the [[Canadian Soccer Association]] complained to FIFA that Wagner should be ineligible to play for the United States based on his appearances for Germany's youth teams. On 2 May 1997, FIFA announced that Wagner was eligible to play for the United States because his games with the German teams were exhibitions, not official matches.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wagner Gets Approval for U.S. Team |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/05/02/sports/wagner-gets-approval-for-us-team.html |accessdate=15 January 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=2 May 1997}}</ref> However, Wagner was rarely called into the U.S. team afterward and he was not named to the squad for the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]].\n\n==Managerial career==\n===Borussia Dortmund II===\nFollowing his playing career, Wagner became a [[Manager (association football)|manager]], working mostly with his former 1. [[FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]] teammate [[J\u00fcrgen Klopp]]. Wagner was appointed as [[Borussia Dortmund II]] manager with effect from 1 July 2011.<ref name=\"dortmundiijob\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/regionalliga/startseite/549307/artikel_david-wagner-coacht-ab-juli-die-bvb-u23.html|title=David Wagner coacht ab Juli die BVB-U23|date=2 March 2011|newspaper=kicker|language=German|trans-title=David Wagner coaches the BVB under-23 club in July|accessdate=8 February 2013}}</ref> He left the role on 31 October 2015, amidst rumours that he was going to join Klopp's backroom staff at [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref name=\"BD-Liverpool\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bvb.de/News/U23/Borussia-Dortmund-und-David-Wagner-beenden-Zusammenarbeit|title=Borussia Dortmund und David Wagner beenden Zusammenarbeit|date=31 October 2015|publisher=Borussia Dortmund GmbH & Co.|language=German|trans-title=Borussia Dortmund and Wagner reach an agreement|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=David Wagner leaves Dortmund U23 post amid Liverpool links|url=http://www.espnfc.co.uk/borussia-dortmund/story/2694401/david-wagner-leaves-borussia-dortmund-amid-liverpool-links|accessdate=4 November 2015|publisher=ESPN|date=3 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Huddersfield Town===\nOn 5 November 2015, Wagner was appointed manager of English club [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] following the departure of [[Chris Powell]].<ref>{{cite news|title=David Wagner: Huddersfield name ex-Borussia Dortmund man as boss|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34733422|accessdate=5 November 2015|publisher=BBC|date=5 November 2015}}</ref> He brought Christoph B\u00fchler, who had left Borussia Dortmund on 1 November 2015, with him as his assistant.<ref name=\"BD-Liverpool\"/><ref name=\"Guardian Wagner\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/nov/05/huddersfield-town-appoint-david-wagner-manager |title=Huddersfield appoint former Dortmund reserves manager David Wagner |agency=Press Association |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=5 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2016, Wagner brought in 13 players from across the continent, including [[Danny Ward (Welsh footballer)|Danny Ward]], [[Chris L\u00f6we]], and [[Aaron Mooy]]. He took his players on a bonding tour of Sweden, where they had to survive with only basic equipment for a few days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mobile.htafc.com//news/article/2016-17/huddersfield-town-david-wagner-mark-hudson-sweden-pre-season-3164922.aspx|title=David Wagner & Mark Hudson review Huddersfield Town's pre-season camp in Sweden|last=Threlfall-Sykes|first=David|access-date=23 February 2017}}</ref> The team's success in the early [[2016\u201317 Huddersfield Town A.F.C. season|2016\u201317]] season was largely accredited to the squad's tight bond, something that Wagner claimed was a direct result of this Sweden trip. A few weeks later, they visited Austria and kept two clean sheets in matches against [[Bundesliga]] sides [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]] and [[FC Ingolstadt 04|Ingolstadt 04]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.examiner.co.uk/sport/football/news/fc-ingolstadt-friendly-rounds-huddersfield-11677445|title=FC Ingolstadt friendly rounds off Huddersfield Town pre season|last=Porter|first=Alexandra|date=28 July 2016|newspaper=Huddersfield Examiner|access-date= 22 February 2017}}</ref> After an unbeaten start to the 2016\u201317 season, Huddersfield were top of the table at the start of September,<ref name=\":0\" /> including a win at [[St James' Park]] against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36993966|title=Newcastle United 1\u20132 Huddersfield Town|date=13 August 2016|work=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/10545284/sky-bet-championship-round-up-huddersfield-town-go-top-of-the-league-as-newcastle-win-again|title=Sky Bet Championship round-up: Huddersfield town go top of the league as Newcastle win again|last=Dale|first=James|date=20 August 2016|publisher=Sky Sports|access-date= 22 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 May 2017, Huddersfield secured promotion to the [[Premier League]] for the [[2017\u201318 Premier League|2017\u201318 season]], following a victory on penalties in the [[2017 EFL Championship play-off Final|play-off final]] against [[Reading F.C.|Reading]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/football/38395763|title=How Huddersfield won promotion to the Premier League|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=30 November 2017|work=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/may/29/huddersfield-david-wagner-players-legends-achieved-small-budget-reading|title=David Wagner praises Huddersfield 'legends' after promotion to top flight|date= 29 May 2017|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref> On 30 June 2017, Wagner signed an improved two-year contract.\n<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40418395|title=David Wagner: Huddersfield Town boss extends contract with Premier League side|date=30 June 2017|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> He was praised for his achievements in keeping Huddersfield in the Premier League at the end of the 2017\u201318 season, a feat regarded by bookmakers as improbable and described by ''[[The Guardian]]'' as \"the Premier League's greatest survival story\", with Wagner in particular noted as a leader of rare charisma and intelligence.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Doyle |title=Huddersfield staying up is Premier League's greatest survival story| work=The Guardian |date=10 May 2018 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/may/10/huddersfield-stay-up-premier-league-david-wagner-money |accessdate=14 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 January 2019, Wagner and Huddersfield Town agreed to terminate his contract by mutual consent, with the team in last place and eight points from safety.<ref>{{cite news |title=David Wagner: Huddersfield Town manager leaves club by mutual consent |work=BBC Sport |date=14 January 2019 |accessdate=14 January 2019 |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46864005}}</ref>\n\n===Schalke 04===\nOn 9 May 2019, Wagner returned to Germany and got appointed as manager of Bundesliga club [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]] for the [[2019\u201320 FC Schalke 04 season|2019\u201320 season]], with a three-year contract lasting until 30 June 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://schalke04.de/en/team/david-wagner-becomes-new-head-coach-schalke-04/|title=David Wagner becomes new head coach of Schalke 04|website=Schalke 04|accessdate=9 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nWagner is married. The couple has two daughters, Lynn and Lea. His daughter Lea works as a sports presenter for the public regional broadcasting company [[S\u00fcdwestrundfunk|SWR]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.swr.de/unternehmen/kommunikation/pressemeldungen/swrsport-lea-wagner-2019-108.html|title=Lea Wagner moderiert \u201eSWR Sport\u201c|first=|last=|work=|publisher=|date=|accessdate=18 March 2020|language=de}}</ref> She is also part of the team of reporters for [[Sportschau]] on [[ARD (broadcaster)|ARD]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.focus.de/sport/frisches-gesicht-tochter-von-schalke-trainer-wagner-wird-sportschau-moderatorin_id_11661253.html|title=Tochter von Schalke-Trainer Wagner wird Sportschau-Moderatorin|first=|last=|work=|publisher=|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|language=de}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|match played 7 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team\n!rowspan=2|From\n!rowspan=2|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n!rowspan=2|{{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\n|-\n!{{abbr|P|Matches played}}!!{{abbr|W|Matches won}}!!{{abbr|D|Matches drawn}}!!{{abbr|L|Matches lost}}!!{{abbr|Win %|Win percentage}}\t\t\n|-\t\n|align=left|[[Borussia Dortmund II]]\n|align=left|1 July 2011\n|align=left|31 October 2015\n{{WDL|164|57|47|60|decimals=1}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1-bundesliga/borussia-dortmund-ii-1291/trainer.html |title=Borussia Dortmund II \u2013 Trainerhistorie |website=Kicker |publisher=Olympia-Verlag |accessdate=26 May 2019 |language=German |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526214553/https://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1-bundesliga/borussia-dortmund-ii-1291/trainer.html |archive-date=26 May 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]\n|align=left|9 November 2015\n|align=left|14 January 2019\n{{WDL|154|51|33|70|decimals=1}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.soccerbase.com/managers/manager.sd?manager_id=3784 |title=Managers: David Wagner |website=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]]\n|align=left|1 July 2019\n|align=left|Present\n{{WDL|29|12|10|7|decimals=1}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.soccerbase.com/managers/manager.sd?manager_id=3784 |title=Managers: David Wagner |website=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n{{WDLtot|347|120|90|137|decimals=1}}\n!\u2014\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''Schalke 04'''\n*[[UEFA Cup]]: [[1996\u201397 UEFA Cup|1996\u201397]]<ref name=\"Guardian Wagner\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.htafc.com/news/article/huddersfield-town-david-wagner-head-coach-profile-2785670.aspx |title=Learn more about the new arrival |last=Threlfall-Sykes |first=David |publisher=[[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.]] |date=5 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Manager===\n'''Huddersfield Town'''\n*[[EFL Championship play-offs]]: [[2017 English Football League play-offs#Championship|2017]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39995791 |title=Huddersfield Town 0\u20130 Reading |first=Ian |last=Woodcock |work=BBC Sport |date=29 May 2017 |accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[EFL Championship]] Manager of the Year: 2016\u201317{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n*[[Premier League Manager of the Month]]: [[2017\u201318 Premier League#Monthly awards|August 2017]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/managers/13476/David-Wagner/overview |title=Manager profile: David Wagner |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n*[[EFL Championship Manager of the Month]]: [[2016\u201317 EFL Championship#Monthly awards|August 2016]], February 2017{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerway|203317}}\n\n{{FC Schalke 04 squad}}\n{{Bundesliga managers}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Managerial positions\n| list1 = \n{{Huddersfield Town A.F.C. managers}}\n{{FC Schalke 04 managers}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wagner, David}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Gro\u00df-Gerau (district)]]\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:American soccer players]]\n[[Category:American soccer coaches]]\n[[Category:United States men's international soccer players]]\n[[Category:Germany under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Thai descent]]\n[[Category:German people of Thai descent]]\n[[Category:German people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Eintracht Frankfurt players]]\n[[Category:Eintracht Frankfurt II players]]\n[[Category:1. FSV Mainz 05 players]]\n[[Category:FC Schalke 04 players]]\n[[Category:FC G\u00fctersloh 2000 players]]\n[[Category:SV Waldhof Mannheim players]]\n[[Category:SV Darmstadt 98 players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:2. Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Regionalliga players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Huddersfield Town A.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:3. Liga managers]]\n[[Category:English Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Premier League managers]]\n[[Category:FC Schalke 04 managers]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga managers]]\n[[Category:German football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in England]]\n[[Category:German expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:German expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Borussia Dortmund II managers]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Hesse]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = David Wagner\n| image = David Wagner 110919 1.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Wagner as [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]] manager in 2019\n| fullname = David Wagner<ref name=BDFutbol>{{cite web |url=https://www.bdfutbol.com/en/l/l98580.html |title=Wagner: David Wagner: Manager |publisher=BDFutbol |accessdate=3 May 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1971|10|19|df=y}}<ref name=BDFutbol/>\n| birth_place = [[Frankfurt]], West Germany<ref name=\"ruhr24\">{{cite web|title=Sex, Drugs and Rock'n'Roll: Schalke-Trainer David Wagner gibt intime Einblicke \u00fcber seine Mutter|periodical=|publisher=|url=https://www.ruhr24.de/s04/david-wagner-einblicke-sex-drugs-rocknroll-mutter-13097138.html|url-status=|format=|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|last=|date=|year=|language=de|pages=|quote=}}</ref>\n| height = 1.80 m<ref name=BDFutbol/>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| currentclub = [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]] (manager)\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = SV Geinsheim\n| years1 = 1990\u20131991\n| clubs1 = [[Eintracht Frankfurt]]\n| caps1 = 1\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1991\u20131995\n| clubs2 = [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]]\n| caps2 = 94\n| goals2 = 19\n| years3 = 1995\u20131997\n| clubs3 = [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]]\n| caps3 = 29\n| goals3 = 2\n| years4 = 1997\u20131999\n| clubs4 = [[FC G\u00fctersloh]]\n| caps4 = 49\n| goals4 = 7\n| years5 = 1999\n| clubs5 = [[SV Waldhof Mannheim|Waldhof Mannheim]]\n| caps5 = 5\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 1999\u20132002\n| clubs6 = [[SV Darmstadt 98|Darmstadt 98]]\n| caps6 = 76\n| goals6 = 21\n| years7 = 2002\u20132004\n| clubs7 = [[TSG Weinheim]]\n| caps7 = \n| goals7 = \n| years8 = 2004\u20132006\n| clubs8 = Germania Pfungstadt\n| caps8 = \n| goals8 = \n| nationalyears1 = 1992\n| nationalteam1 = [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany U21]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1996\u20131998\n| nationalteam2 = [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 8\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2011\u20132015\n| managerclubs1 = [[Borussia Dortmund II]]\n| manageryears2 = 2015\u20132019\n| managerclubs2 = [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]\n| manageryears3 = 2019\u2013\n| managerclubs3 = [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]]\n}}\n'''David Wagner''' (born 19 October 1971) is a German-American professional [[Manager (association football)|football manager]] and former [[Football player|player]] who is the manager of [[Bundesliga]] club [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]].\n\nHe grew up in West Germany and made his professional debut with [[Eintracht Frankfurt]] in 1990 and played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]] for several clubs in the first and second divisions of [[German football league system|German football]]. The son of an American father and German mother, Wagner played for the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]], earning eight caps between 1996 and 1998.\n\nFrom 2011 to 2015, he managed [[Borussia Dortmund II]]. Wagner left in November 2015 to take the job at [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]], which he led to the [[Premier League]] via the [[2017 EFL Championship play-off Final]]. He left Huddersfield in January 2019, soon afterwards taking the manager position at Bundesliga club Schalke 04 in July 2019.\n\n==Early life==\nWagner was born in [[Frankfurt]], West Germany.<ref name=\"ruhr24\" /> His biological father is from [[Thailand]],<ref name=\"11 Freunde\">{{Cite web|url=https://11freunde.de/artikel/wie-david-wagner-schalke-wiederbelebt/page/1|title=Wagners gr\u00f6\u00dfte Leistung|first=Ron|last=Ulrich|work=11 Freunde|publisher=11 Freunde GmbH & Co. KG|date=29 September 2019|accessdate=20 December 2019|language=de}}</ref> his mother is German.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://americansoccernow.com/articles/american-david-wagner-now-coaching-in-england|title=ASN: American David Wagner Now Coaching in England|website=americansoccernow.com|access-date=14 January 2019}}</ref> Before his birth, Wagner's mother married an American.<ref name=\"11 Freunde\" />\n\n==Playing career==\nIn 1996, Wagner was recruited along with fellow [[Bundesliga]] player [[Michael Mason (soccer)|Michael Mason]] by manager [[Steve Sampson]] into the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]] despite never having seen them play. Sampson had been recommended Wagner and Mason and made aware of their American background by U.S. player [[Thomas Dooley]], who like them was also raised in Germany. Wagner had a United States passport, but had played for Germany's [[Germany national under-18 football team|U18]] and [[Germany national under-21 football team|U21]] teams earlier in his career. This gave him additional credibility with Sampson but posed a problem as he risked being considered ineligible to play for the United States.\n\nWagner made his debut in a friendly 3\u20131 win over [[El Salvador national football team|El Salvador]] in Los Angeles on 30 August 1996, in which he was substituted at half-time for [[Brian McBride]]. He made five appearances the following year and two more in 1998, all but one as a starter.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wagner, David |url=https://www.national-football-teams.com/player/28278/David_Wagner.html |publisher=National Football Teams |accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=1996 Lineups |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/mens-national-team/lineups/1996-lineups |publisher=US Soccer |accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1997, after [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]] lost to the United States in a [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|World Cup qualifying]] match in which Wagner played, the [[Canadian Soccer Association]] complained to FIFA that Wagner should be ineligible to play for the United States based on his appearances for Germany's youth teams. On 2 May 1997, FIFA announced that Wagner was eligible to play for the United States because his games with the German teams were exhibitions, not official matches.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wagner Gets Approval for U.S. Team |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/05/02/sports/wagner-gets-approval-for-us-team.html |accessdate=15 January 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=2 May 1997}}</ref> However, Wagner was rarely called into the U.S. team afterward and he was not named to the squad for the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]].\n\n==Managerial career==\n===Borussia Dortmund II===\nFollowing his playing career, Wagner became a [[Manager (association football)|manager]], working mostly with his former 1. [[FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]] teammate [[J\u00fcrgen Klopp]]. Wagner was appointed as [[Borussia Dortmund II]] manager with effect from 1 July 2011.<ref name=\"dortmundiijob\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/regionalliga/startseite/549307/artikel_david-wagner-coacht-ab-juli-die-bvb-u23.html|title=David Wagner coacht ab Juli die BVB-U23|date=2 March 2011|newspaper=kicker|language=German|trans-title=David Wagner coaches the BVB under-23 club in July|accessdate=8 February 2013}}</ref> He left the role on 31 October 2015, amidst rumours that he was going to join Klopp's backroom staff at [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref name=\"BD-Liverpool\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bvb.de/News/U23/Borussia-Dortmund-und-David-Wagner-beenden-Zusammenarbeit|title=Borussia Dortmund und David Wagner beenden Zusammenarbeit|date=31 October 2015|publisher=Borussia Dortmund GmbH & Co.|language=German|trans-title=Borussia Dortmund and Wagner reach an agreement|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=David Wagner leaves Dortmund U23 post amid Liverpool links|url=http://www.espnfc.co.uk/borussia-dortmund/story/2694401/david-wagner-leaves-borussia-dortmund-amid-liverpool-links|accessdate=4 November 2015|publisher=ESPN|date=3 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Huddersfield Town===\nOn 5 November 2015, Wagner was appointed manager of English club [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] following the departure of [[Chris Powell]].<ref>{{cite news|title=David Wagner: Huddersfield name ex-Borussia Dortmund man as boss|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34733422|accessdate=5 November 2015|publisher=BBC|date=5 November 2015}}</ref> He brought Christoph B\u00fchler, who had left Borussia Dortmund on 1 November 2015, with him as his assistant.<ref name=\"BD-Liverpool\"/><ref name=\"Guardian Wagner\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/nov/05/huddersfield-town-appoint-david-wagner-manager |title=Huddersfield appoint former Dortmund reserves manager David Wagner |agency=Press Association |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=5 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2016, Wagner brought in 13 players from across the continent, including [[Danny Ward (Welsh footballer)|Danny Ward]], [[Chris L\u00f6we]], and [[Aaron Mooy]]. He took his players on a bonding tour of Sweden, where they had to survive with only basic equipment for a few days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mobile.htafc.com//news/article/2016-17/huddersfield-town-david-wagner-mark-hudson-sweden-pre-season-3164922.aspx|title=David Wagner & Mark Hudson review Huddersfield Town's pre-season camp in Sweden|last=Threlfall-Sykes|first=David|access-date=23 February 2017}}</ref> The team's success in the early [[2016\u201317 Huddersfield Town A.F.C. season|2016\u201317]] season was largely accredited to the squad's tight bond, something that Wagner claimed was a direct result of this Sweden trip. A few weeks later, they visited Austria and kept two clean sheets in matches against [[Bundesliga]] sides [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]] and [[FC Ingolstadt 04|Ingolstadt 04]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.examiner.co.uk/sport/football/news/fc-ingolstadt-friendly-rounds-huddersfield-11677445|title=FC Ingolstadt friendly rounds off Huddersfield Town pre season|last=Porter|first=Alexandra|date=28 July 2016|newspaper=Huddersfield Examiner|access-date= 22 February 2017}}</ref> After an unbeaten start to the 2016\u201317 season, Huddersfield were top of the table at the start of September,<ref name=\":0\" /> including a win at [[St James' Park]] against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36993966|title=Newcastle United 1\u20132 Huddersfield Town|date=13 August 2016|work=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/10545284/sky-bet-championship-round-up-huddersfield-town-go-top-of-the-league-as-newcastle-win-again|title=Sky Bet Championship round-up: Huddersfield town go top of the league as Newcastle win again|last=Dale|first=James|date=20 August 2016|publisher=Sky Sports|access-date= 22 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 May 2017, Huddersfield secured promotion to the [[Premier League]] for the [[2017\u201318 Premier League|2017\u201318 season]], following a victory on penalties in the [[2017 EFL Championship play-off Final|play-off final]] against [[Reading F.C.|Reading]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/football/38395763|title=How Huddersfield won promotion to the Premier League|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=30 November 2017|work=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/may/29/huddersfield-david-wagner-players-legends-achieved-small-budget-reading|title=David Wagner praises Huddersfield 'legends' after promotion to top flight|date= 29 May 2017|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref> On 30 June 2017, Wagner signed an improved two-year contract.\n<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40418395|title=David Wagner: Huddersfield Town boss extends contract with Premier League side|date=30 June 2017|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> He was praised for his achievements in keeping Huddersfield in the Premier League at the end of the 2017\u201318 season, a feat regarded by bookmakers as improbable and described by ''[[The Guardian]]'' as \"the Premier League's greatest survival story\", with Wagner in particular noted as a leader of rare charisma and intelligence.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Doyle |title=Huddersfield staying up is Premier League's greatest survival story| work=The Guardian |date=10 May 2018 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/may/10/huddersfield-stay-up-premier-league-david-wagner-money |accessdate=14 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 January 2019, Wagner and Huddersfield Town agreed to terminate his contract by mutual consent, with the team in last place and eight points from safety.<ref>{{cite news |title=David Wagner: Huddersfield Town manager leaves club by mutual consent |work=BBC Sport |date=14 January 2019 |accessdate=14 January 2019 |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46864005}}</ref>\n\n===Schalke 04===\nOn 9 May 2019, Wagner returned to Germany and got appointed as manager of Bundesliga club [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]] for the [[2019\u201320 FC Schalke 04 season|2019\u201320 season]], with a three-year contract lasting until 30 June 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://schalke04.de/en/team/david-wagner-becomes-new-head-coach-schalke-04/|title=David Wagner becomes new head coach of Schalke 04|website=Schalke 04|accessdate=9 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nWagner is married. The couple has two daughters, Lynn and Lea. His daughter Lea works as a sports presenter for the public regional broadcasting company [[S\u00fcdwestrundfunk|SWR]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.swr.de/unternehmen/kommunikation/pressemeldungen/swrsport-lea-wagner-2019-108.html|title=Lea Wagner moderiert \u201eSWR Sport\u201c|first=|last=|work=|publisher=|date=|accessdate=18 March 2020|language=de}}</ref> She is also part of the team of reporters for [[Sportschau]] on [[ARD (broadcaster)|ARD]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.focus.de/sport/frisches-gesicht-tochter-von-schalke-trainer-wagner-wird-sportschau-moderatorin_id_11661253.html|title=Tochter von Schalke-Trainer Wagner wird Sportschau-Moderatorin|first=|last=|work=|publisher=|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|language=de}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|match played 7 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team\n!rowspan=2|From\n!rowspan=2|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n!rowspan=2|{{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\n|-\n!{{abbr|P|Matches played}}!!{{abbr|W|Matches won}}!!{{abbr|D|Matches drawn}}!!{{abbr|L|Matches lost}}!!{{abbr|Win %|Win percentage}}\t\t\n|-\t\n|align=left|[[Borussia Dortmund II]]\n|align=left|1 July 2011\n|align=left|31 October 2015\n{{WDL|164|57|47|60|decimals=1}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1-bundesliga/borussia-dortmund-ii-1291/trainer.html |title=Borussia Dortmund II \u2013 Trainerhistorie |website=Kicker |publisher=Olympia-Verlag |accessdate=26 May 2019 |language=German |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526214553/https://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1-bundesliga/borussia-dortmund-ii-1291/trainer.html |archive-date=26 May 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]\n|align=left|9 November 2015\n|align=left|14 January 2019\n{{WDL|154|51|33|70|decimals=1}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.soccerbase.com/managers/manager.sd?manager_id=3784 |title=Managers: David Wagner |website=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]]\n|align=left|1 July 2019\n|align=left|Present\n{{WDL|29|12|10|7|decimals=1}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.soccerbase.com/managers/manager.sd?manager_id=3784 |title=Managers: David Wagner |website=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n{{WDLtot|347|120|90|137|decimals=1}}\n!\u2014\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''Schalke 04'''\n*[[UEFA Cup]]: [[1996\u201397 UEFA Cup|1996\u201397]]<ref name=\"Guardian Wagner\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.htafc.com/news/article/huddersfield-town-david-wagner-head-coach-profile-2785670.aspx |title=Learn more about the new arrival |last=Threlfall-Sykes |first=David |publisher=[[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.]] |date=5 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Manager===\n'''Huddersfield Town'''\n*[[EFL Championship play-offs]]: [[2017 English Football League play-offs#Championship|2017]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39995791 |title=Huddersfield Town 0\u20130 Reading |first=Ian |last=Woodcock |work=BBC Sport |date=29 May 2017 |accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[EFL Championship]] Manager of the Year: 2016\u201317{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n*[[Premier League Manager of the Month]]: [[2017\u201318 Premier League#Monthly awards|August 2017]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/managers/13476/David-Wagner/overview |title=Manager profile: David Wagner |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n*[[EFL Championship Manager of the Month]]: [[2016\u201317 EFL Championship#Monthly awards|August 2016]], February 2017{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerway|203317}}\n\n{{FC Schalke 04 squad}}\n{{Bundesliga managers}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Managerial positions\n| list1 = \n{{Huddersfield Town A.F.C. managers}}\n{{FC Schalke 04 managers}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wagner, David}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Gro\u00df-Gerau (district)]]\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:American soccer players]]\n[[Category:American soccer coaches]]\n[[Category:United States men's international soccer players]]\n[[Category:Germany under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Thai descent]]\n[[Category:German people of Thai descent]]\n[[Category:German people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Eintracht Frankfurt players]]\n[[Category:Eintracht Frankfurt II players]]\n[[Category:1. FSV Mainz 05 players]]\n[[Category:FC Schalke 04 players]]\n[[Category:FC G\u00fctersloh 2000 players]]\n[[Category:SV Waldhof Mannheim players]]\n[[Category:SV Darmstadt 98 players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:2. Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Regionalliga players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Huddersfield Town A.